Exercise 2.1

  1. \[ P(B|A) > P(B) \] If a person enjoy an award-winning books, it means that he likes this author’s writing style. Therefore, he will be more probable to be interested in the same author’s book.
  2. \[ P(B|A) < P(B) \] Given today’s temperature is 0 degrees Fahrenheit, it is less likely that tomorrow’s temperature will suddenly get to 60 degrees.
  3. \[ P(B|A) > P(B) \] If the authors only got 3 hours of sleep last night, it will be more likely that the authors will make several typos today because sleeping less will cause disattraction.
  4. \[ P(B|A) > P(B) \] If my friend includes three hashtags in their tweets, the tweet is more likely to get retweeted. Because the more the number of hashtags is, the more people see this tweet.

Exercise 2.2

  1. \[ P(B|A) = 0.73 \] This is a conditional probability.
  2. \[ P(A) = 0.2 \] This is a marginal probability.
  3. \[ P(D) = 0.15 \] This is a marginal probability.
  4. \[ P(C|D) = 0.91 \] This is a conditional probability.
  5. \[ P(F∩E) \] This is a joint probability.
  6. \[ P(E|F) \] This is a conditional probability.

The posterior probability that the elected maple tree has mold is about 63.7%.

d.Given the selected tree is a maple tree, the probability of the tree having mold increases from 18% to 63.7% because the trees with mold is more likely to be maples (80%) while only 10 percent of healthy trees are maples. The maples trees is more compatible with the trees having mold.

  2. The probability that π = 0.7 and π = 0.75 will decrease while the probability that π = 0.6 and π = 0.65 will increase.

# calculate the likelihood
p <- c(0.6, 0.65, 0.7, 0.75)
lik15 <- dbinom(10,15,p)
lik15
## [1] 0.1859378 0.2123387 0.2061304 0.1651460
# Calculate the normalizing constant
nc15 <- 0.3*0.1859378 + 0.4*0.2123387 +0.2*0.2061304 + 0.1*0.1651460

# calculate the posterior results of each π
pmf_0.6_exercise15 <- 0.3*0.1859378 /nc15
pmf_0.65_exercise15 <- 0.4*0.2123387/nc15
pmf_0.7_exercise15 <- 0.2*0.2061304/nc15
pmf_0.75_exercise15 <- 0.1*0.1651460/nc15


pmf_0.6_exercise15
## [1] 0.2810745
pmf_0.65_exercise15
## [1] 0.4279782
pmf_0.7_exercise15
## [1] 0.2077325
pmf_0.75_exercise15
## [1] 0.08321479

d.The likelihood part is evaluating the compatibility of each π with the fact that 10 out of 15 hatchlings would survive for at least 1 week. The normalizing constant “nc15” is used to balance the likelihood and prior model, which can be more easy for us to do comparison.

Exercise 2.20

# Define possible status
image <- data.frame(type = c("cat", "noncat"))
# Define the prior model
prior <- c(0.08, 0.92)
# Simulate 10,000 images
set.seed(20)
image_sim <- sample_n(image, size = 10000, weight = prior, replace = TRUE)

image_sim |> 
  tabyl(type) |>
  adorn_totals("row")
##    type     n percent
##     cat   811  0.0811
##  noncat  9189  0.9189
##   Total 10000  1.0000
image_sim <- image_sim |> 
  mutate(algorithm = case_when(type == "cat" ~ 0.8,type == "noncat" ~ 0.5))

data <- c("correct", "wrong")
set.seed(30)
image_sim <- image_sim |>
  group_by(1:n()) |> 
  mutate(algorithmornot = sample(data, size = 1, 
                        prob = c(algorithm, 1-algorithm)))
image_sim |>
  tabyl(algorithmornot, type) %>% 
  adorn_totals(c("col","row"))
##  algorithmornot cat noncat Total
##         correct 654   4573  5227
##           wrong 157   4616  4773
##           Total 811   9189 10000
654/(654+4616)
## [1] 0.1240987

The approximate probability that an image is actually a cat if the algorithm identifies it as a cat is about 12.4%.

Exercise 2.21

# Define possible status
status <- data.frame(type = c("deseased", "healthy"))
# Define the prior model
prior <- c(0.03, 0.97)
# Simulate 10,000 people
set.seed(21)
status_sim <- sample_n(status, size = 10000, weight = prior, replace = TRUE)

status_sim |> 
  tabyl(type) |>
  adorn_totals("row")
##      type     n percent
##  deseased   336  0.0336
##   healthy  9664  0.9664
##     Total 10000  1.0000
status_sim <- status_sim |> 
  mutate(test = case_when(type == "deseased" ~ 0.93,type == "healthy" ~ 0.07))

data <- c("positive", "negative")
set.seed(22)
status_sim <- status_sim |>
  group_by(1:n()) |> 
  mutate(testornot = sample(data, size = 1, 
                        prob = c(test, 1-test)))
status_sim |>
  tabyl(testornot, type) %>% 
  adorn_totals(c("col","row"))

  filter(testornot == "positive") |>

  adorn_totals("row")
